ittle agency, what becomes of these children as they grow and assume new roles and identities, only to risk losing legal protection as they reach eighteen? Through international studies and crucially the voices of the young migrants themselves, the book examines the narratives they present and the frameworks of culture and legislation into which they are placed. It challenges existing policy and questions, from a social justice perspective, what the treatment of this group tells us about our systems and the cultural presuppositions on which they depend.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aImmigrant childrenxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 0aImmigrant childrenxLegal status, laws, etczGreat Britain. 0aImmigrant childrenxSocial conditionszGreat Britain. 0aSocial justicezGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aBruzzone, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClayton, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClayton, Sue, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDrammeh, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubs, Alf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGifford, Sandra M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález-Araiza, Luis Enrique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGupta, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGupta, Anna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHughes, Gillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLidén, Hilde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobinson, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct